==English==
===Etymology===
Held to be named after [[w:Charles Baillie, 2nd Baron Lamington|Charles Baillie, 2nd Baron Lamington]], who was [[governor]] of [[Queensland]] from 1896 to 1901, but this is uncertain.  The first publication of this derivation is by John Hepworth in ''Nation Review'' July 1977.  Earlier Sydney Baker in ''The Australian Language'' (2nd edition 1966) describes lamington referring to firstly the [[Homburg hat]] worn by Baron Lamington and secondly elsewhere as referring to the cake.  He doesn't associate the cake with the Baron, suggesting that theory was not current in the 1960s.  (Reference: [http://www.anu.edu.au/andc/ozwords/May_99/6._lamington.htm Australian National University OzWords May 1999].)

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# An small Australian cake made with [[sponge]] cake covered with chocolate and [[desiccated]] [[coconut]].

